[2026-03-13T17:47:31Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011sqw4C9PpA853ucpG3b61r","type":"tool_result","content":"     1Рєњ# Workflows\n     2Рєњ\n     3РєњCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4Рєњ\n     5Рєњ## Workflow Locations\n     6Рєњ\n     7РєњCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8Рєњ\n     9Рєњ**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) Рђћ Run inside a Docker\n    10Рєњcontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11Рєњstandard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12Рєњ\n    13Рєњ**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) Рђћ Run on the host machine as the daemon\n    14Рєњprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15Рєњdispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16Рєњpoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17Рєњ\n    18РєњA single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n    19Рєњuses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n    20Рєњ\n    21Рєњ| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n    22Рєњ|-------|--------------|---------|\n    23Рєњ| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n    24Рєњ| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n    25Рєњ| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n    26Рєњ\n    27РєњOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\n    28Рєњsingle-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n    29Рєњ\n    30РєњThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n    31Рєњobject with the following fields:\n    32Рєњ\n    33Рєњ| Field | Required | Description |\n    34Рєњ|-------|----------|-------------|\n    35Рєњ| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n    36Рєњ| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n    37Рєњ| `title` | no | Short summary |\n    38Рєњ| `description` | no | Full description |\n    39Рєњ| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n    40Рєњ\n    41РєњThe daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\n    42Рєњcompatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\n    43РєњTasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\n    44Рєњreassignment.\n    45Рєњ\n    46РєњThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    47Рєњfile is a parse error.\n    48Рєњ\n    49Рєњ## Concepts\n    50Рєњ\n    51Рєњ| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    52Рєњ|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    53Рєњ| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    54Рєњ| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    55Рєњ| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    56Рєњ| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    57Рєњ| done     | Built-in terminal step Рђћ successful completion                     |\n    58Рєњ| abort    | Built-in terminal step Рђћ failure with error reporting              |\n    59Рєњ\n    60Рєњ## Step Types\n    61Рєњ\n    62РєњStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    63Рєњ\n    64Рєњ**agent** (has `prompt`) Рђћ Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    65Рєњto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    66Рєњcontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    67Рєњ\n    68Рєњ**script** (has `run`) Рђћ Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    69Рєњany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    70Рєњ\n    71Рєњ**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) Рђћ Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    72Рєњuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    73Рєњ\n    74РєњA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    75Рєњparse error.\n    76Рєњ\n    77Рєњ## DSL Syntax\n    78Рєњ\n    79Рєњ```\n    80Рєњworkflow \"develop\" {\n    81Рєњ  container {\n    82Рєњ    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    83Рєњ    agent_command = \"claude\"\n    84Рєњ  }\n    85Рєњ\n    86Рєњ  step implement {\n    87Рєњ    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    88Рєњ    results = [success, fail]\n    89Рєњ  }\n    90Рєњ\n    91Рєњ  step test {\n    92Рєњ    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    93Рєњ    results = [success, fail]\n    94Рєњ  }\n    95Рєњ\n    96Рєњ  step fix {\n    97Рєњ    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    98Рєњ    max_attempts = \"3\"\n    99Рєњ    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   100Рєњ  }\n   101Рєњ\n   102Рєњ  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n   103Рєњ  implement:success -> test\n   104Рєњ  implement:fail    -> abort\n   105Рєњ  test:success      -> done\n   106Рєњ  test:fail         -> fix\n   107Рєњ  fix:success       -> test\n   108Рєњ  fix:fail          -> abort\n   109Рєњ  fix:give-up       -> abort\n   110Рєњ}\n   111Рєњ```\n   112Рєњ\n   113Рєњ## Key Properties\n   114Рєњ\n   115Рєњ**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n   116Рєњfield makes it a script step.\n   117Рєњ\n   118Рєњ**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n   119Рєњreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n   120Рєњ\n   121Рєњ**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n   122Рєњexisting ones by rewiring Рђћ without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n   123РєњCloche's self-evolution feature.\n   124Рєњ\n   125Рєњ**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n   126Рєњwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   127Рєњ\n   128Рєњ## Wire Output Mappings\n   129Рєњ\n   130РєњWires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   131Рєњthem as environment variables into the target step:\n   132Рєњ\n   133Рєњ```\n   134Рєњstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   135Рєњ```\n   136Рєњ\n   137РєњThe general form:\n   138Рєњ\n   139Рєњ```\n   140РєњFROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   141Рєњ```\n   142Рєњ\n   143РєњWhere `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   144Рєњstarting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   145Рєњ\n   146Рєњ| Expression | Meaning |\n   147Рєњ|---|---|\n   148Рєњ| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   149Рєњ| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   150Рєњ| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   151Рєњ| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   152Рєњ| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   153Рєњ\n   154РєњIf the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   155Рєњstructure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   156Рєњvalue is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   157Рєњ\n   158РєњIf two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   159Рєњreturns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   160Рєњwires to different steps without conflict.\n   161Рєњ\n   162Рєњ## Workflow-Level Configuration Blocks\n   163Рєњ\n   164РєњWorkflows support a configuration block at the workflow level to set defaults for all\n   165Рєњsteps. The block name depends on the workflow location:\n   166Рєњ\n   167Рєњ**`container {}`** Рђћ For container workflows. Sets container image, agent command, and\n   168Рєњnetwork allowlist.\n   169Рєњ\n   170Рєњ```\n   171Рєњworkflow \"develop\" {\n   172Рєњ  container {\n   173Рєњ    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n   174Рєњ    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   175Рєњ    agent_args = \"-p --dangerously-skip-permissions\"\n   176Рєњ  }\n   177Рєњ  ...\n   178Рєњ}\n   179Рєњ```\n   180Рєњ\n   181РєњSupported keys: `image`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`, `network_allow`.\n   182Рєњ\n   183Рєњ**`host {}`** Рђћ For host workflows (`host.cloche`). Sets agent defaults for agent steps\n   184Рєњrunning on the host machine.\n   185Рєњ\n   186Рєњ```\n   187Рєњworkflow \"main\" {\n   188Рєњ  host {\n   189Рєњ    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   190Рєњ  }\n   191Рєњ  ...\n   192Рєњ}\n   193Рєњ```\n   194Рєњ\n   195РєњSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   196Рєњ\n   197РєњStep-level `agent_command` and `agent_args` override workflow-level defaults. The\n   198Рєњresolution order is: step-level > workflow-level block > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env\n   199Рєњvar > default `claude`.\n   200Рєњ\n   201Рєњ## Host Workflow Example\n   202Рєњ\n   203РєњA three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\n   204Рєњworkflows:\n   205Рєњ\n   206Рєњ```\n   207Рєњ# .cloche/host.cloche Рђћ runs on the host machine\n   208Рєњ\n   209Рєњworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   210Рєњ  step fetch-tickets {\n   211Рєњ    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   212Рєњ    results = [success, fail]\n   213Рєњ  }\n   214Рєњ\n   215Рєњ  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   216Рєњ  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   217Рєњ}\n   218Рєњ\n   219Рєњworkflow \"main\" {\n   220Рєњ  host {\n   221Рєњ    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   222Рєњ  }\n   223Рєњ\n   224Рєњ  step prepare-prompt {\n   225Рєњ    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   226Рєњ    results = [success, fail]\n   227Рєњ  }\n   228Рєњ\n   229Рєњ  step develop {\n   230Рєњ    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   231Рєњ    results       = [success, fail]\n   232Рєњ  }\n   233Рєњ\n   234Рєњ  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   235Рєњ  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   236Рєњ  develop:success        -> done\n   237Рєњ  develop:fail           -> done\n   238Рєњ}\n   239Рєњ\n   240Рєњworkflow \"finalize\" {\n   241Рєњ  step push-for-review {\n   242Рєњ    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   243Рєњ    results = [success, fail]\n   244Рєњ  }\n   245Рєњ\n   246Рєњ  push-for-review:success -> done\n   247Рєњ  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   248Рєњ}\n   249Рєњ```\n   250Рєњ\n   251РєњThe daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\n   252Рєњruns `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\n   253РєњThe `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   254РєњThe `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\n   255РєњThe `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n   256Рєњ`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n   257Рєњ\n   258Рєњ## Execution Model\n   259Рєњ\n   260Рєњ**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   261Рєњcontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   262Рєњwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   263РєњAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   264Рєњ\n   265Рєњ**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n   266Рєњ`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\n   267Рєњin three phases (list-tasks Рєњ main Рєњ finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\n   268Рєњworking directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\n   269Рєњif the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\n   270Рєњhost-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\n   271Рєњruns via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n   272Рєњ`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\n   273Рєњpoints to the actual project directory.\n   274Рєњ"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2090add2-0fe6-4270-9f3b-b52deb6bac91","uuid":"9f335a1c-656f-475c-a5c2-cfc64535e5d8","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md","content":"# Workflows\n\nCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n\n## Workflow Locations\n\nCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n\n**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) Рђћ Run inside a Docker\ncontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\nstandard workflows for coding tasks.\n\n**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) Рђћ Run on the host machine as the daemon\nprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\ndispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\npoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n\nA single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\nuses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n\n| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n|-------|--------------|---------|\n| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n\nOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\nsingle-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\nobject with the following fields:\n\n| Field | Required | Description |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n| `title` | no | Short summary |\n| `description` | no | Full description |\n| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\ncompatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\nTasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\nreassignment.\n\nThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\nfile is a parse error.\n\n## Concepts\n\n| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n| done     | Built-in terminal step Рђћ successful completion                     |\n| abort    | Built-in terminal step Рђћ failure with error reporting              |\n\n## Step Types\n\nStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n\n**agent** (has `prompt`) Рђћ Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\nto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\ncontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**script** (has `run`) Рђћ Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\nany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) Рђћ Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\nuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n\nA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\nparse error.\n\n## DSL Syntax\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step test {\n    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step fix {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    max_attempts = \"3\"\n    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n  }\n\n  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail    -> abort\n  test:success      -> done\n  test:fail         -> fix\n  fix:success       -> test\n  fix:fail          -> abort\n  fix:give-up       -> abort\n}\n```\n\n## Key Properties\n\n**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\nfield makes it a script step.\n\n**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\nreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n\n**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\nexisting ones by rewiring Рђћ without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\nCloche's self-evolution feature.\n\n**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\nwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n\n## Wire Output Mappings\n\nWires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\nthem as environment variables into the target step:\n\n```\nstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n```\n\nThe general form:\n\n```\nFROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n```\n\nWhere `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\nstarting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n\n| Expression | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n\nIf the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\nstructure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\nvalue is converted to a string for env var injection.\n\nIf two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\nreturns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\nwires to different steps without conflict.\n\n## Workflow-Level Configuration Blocks\n\nWorkflows support a configuration block at the workflow level to set defaults for all\nsteps. The block name depends on the workflow location:\n\n**`container {}`** Рђћ For container workflows. Sets container image, agent command, and\nnetwork allowlist.\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n    agent_args = \"-p --dangerously-skip-permissions\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `image`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`, `network_allow`.\n\n**`host {}`** Рђћ For host workflows (`host.cloche`). Sets agent defaults for agent steps\nrunning on the host machine.\n\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n\nStep-level `agent_command` and `agent_args` override workflow-level defaults. The\nresolution order is: step-level > workflow-level block > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env\nvar > default `claude`.\n\n## Host Workflow Example\n\nA three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\nworkflows:\n\n```\n# .cloche/host.cloche Рђћ runs on the host machine\n\nworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n  step fetch-tickets {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n}\n\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n\nworkflow \"finalize\" {\n  step push-for-review {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  push-for-review:success -> done\n  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\nruns `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\nThe `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\nThe `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\nThe `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n\n## Execution Model\n\n**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\ncontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\nwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\nAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n\n**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\nin three phases (list-tasks Рєњ main Рєњ finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\nworking directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\nif the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\nhost-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\nruns via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\npoints to the actual project directory.\n","numLines":274,"startLine":1,"totalLines":274}}}
